The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Business | Business Briefs
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                   Business Briefs
                              
	 Moscow, April 13: Russian telecom firm Sistema, which recently acquired a controlling stake in Shyam Telelink, will launch its mobile services in India by April 2009. The company will invest Rs 4,000 crore this fiscal to roll out the network. Sistema plans to participate in the auctioning of 3G spectrum when the process starts. The company also plans to increase its stake in Shyam Telelink to 74 per cent in the next two months.                            
	 New Delhi, April 13: The FMCG industry, valued at Rs 746.5 billion in 2006-07, has grown 16 per cent in 2007-08 compared with a 14.5 per cent growth in the previous fiscal, according to a survey by Ficci.                            
	 New Delhi, April 13: A group of ministers, headed by external affairs minister Pranab Mukherjee, will meet on April 29 to resolve the problems faced by special economic zones (SEZ) on taxation and export incentives.                            
	 New Delhi, April 13: The directorate general of civil aviation has drafted fresh guidelines for seaplane services to ensure the safety of such operations. Under the new norms, various kinds of pre-flight inspections and passenger briefings on safety have been made mandatory. The new rules also lay down the requirements of equipment to be fitted on these aircraft.                            
	 Mumbai, April 13: Commodity markets regulator Forward Markets Commission (FMC) said futures trading in the US market was responsible for rising commodity prices whereas the reverse was true in India.                            
	 Mumbai, April 13: Yes Bank plans to jointly set up an asset reconstruction company (ARC) with a US-based financial services conglomerate and three public sector banks, by September. We will launch an ARC by the first half of this fiscal. We will hold a 29.5 per cent stake and the foreign partner a 37.5 per cent, said Rana Kapoor, managing director and CEO of Yes Bank.                            
	 New Delhi, April 13: The Tatas have criticised telecom regulator Trai for ordering an enquiry into the deal between Tata Teleservices and Virgin mobile, based on press reports. The Tatas termed the action unfair.                                                                                                                         
